##Civilian volunteers in crisis: forcing themselves into a super docking platform

Micro-signal. NBWEEKLY

Introduction of function, new media with temperature

He felt like a giant electrical outlet, full of holes, with information and resources being plugged into him, and then he would pull the strings.

By Xie Chan, Li Xujin, editor | Roo

Mei Haoyu, 22, sat in a rented room and ate 13 packets of instant noodles and three large bags of snacks. Every day when he opened his eyes, he started replying to messages asking for help and material information pouring in from all directions, all to his hometown of Wuhan.

The largest case involved one hundred and fifty thousand face masks and 50,000 protective clothing. But at some point, he felt like he was facing a giant black hole that couldn't be filled.

"I'm an unplugged electrical outlet. "

Chongqing Normal University, a junior, "involuntarily" became the centerpiece of a civilian rescue operation.

He had an internship in the media, in the circle of friends to see others self-organized volunteer team, joined in, specializing in helping reporters contact the interview object. Later began to look for supplies, only in the state of logistics blockade, for the reporters left in Wuhan docking protective equipment.

Mei sorted out the information and spread it around the circle of friends, responding faster than he thought.

Within two hours, he had more than 200 friend requests waiting for him to approve them, and for the first three or four hours, he had been making friend requests, taking seven seconds for each friend to change a comment.

He did not even reply to a sentence of energy, "typing hands are shaking, touch the screen finger feeling in a cramp. ".

He didn't go to bed until three in the morning, and at seven in the morning, he was awakened by a sense of anxiety and urgency.

Before he could eat, he sat unkempt on his bed in a rented room, answering messages and missed phone calls, all to make donations. He found the fastest way to reach the materials and can contact the logistics company, put together to send reporters.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"New Year's Eve dinner" by Mei Haoyu.

More material information still pouring in, unable to reply one by one, he pulled everyone into a group, which soon grew to more than 400 people.

From this group, everyone came to him: those who wanted to donate, those who were desperately short of supplies, those who were logistically blocked. For two days, he felt like a giant electrical outlet, full of holes, with information and resources plugged into him, and he tried to connect them.

The smaller items include hundreds of protective clothing, masks, and goggles, while the larger items include one hundred thousand pairs of protective clothing, goggles, and more. Through his hand, comb a lot of information and then wire docking, transport difficulties on their own to find logistics companies to help. Meihaoyu forced to support, coupled with friends to help, has been successful docking feedback over the news.

There were moments when he thought he was facing a giant black hole that could not be filled.

One company raised its own 110,000 p 2 export standard disposable masks, asked Mei Haoyu where is still needed? He called the deputy director of the Health Bureau in Yingcheng to see if they needed it, and as soon as he made his case, they poured out their grievances, "almost all the hospitals are short of anything, " and concluded that it would be better to give them all.

After the city closure of Wuhan on the 23rd, private self-raising materials encountered difficulties in transportation. Mei recalled that 500 sets of protective clothing had to be shipped from Caidian District to Laohekou First People's Hospital for emergency use, "But the local logistics from Wuhan could not leave Wuhan, and the logistics from Xiangyang could not reach Wuhan, and there was a part of the road that we could not do anything about, " he said, the delivery was made with two cars facing each other in the rear.

In fact, since the Wuhan epidemic has been widely concerned, the situation in the surrounding cities has also been repeatedly mentioned. Netizens began to use the phrase "there is more than one Wuhan in Hubei" to call attention to the medical conditions and material needs of surrounding cities.

"there are so many shortages here in Wuhan, and the surrounding county-level cities and towns feel like a black hole, " said Poepoe, a young man who did not return to Wuhan for the Spring Festival, had been holed up in a rental house in Chongqing for days, pushing myself, step by step, to do more docking.

Someone asked him about customs clearance, did not receive professional volunteer training Mei haoyu quickly sent a circle of friends for help. "I'm an unplugged plug, pretending to be plugged in. "

16 hours a day, hunched over a computer, coordinating donations

The information on the shortage of medical supplies that has swept through the circle of friends began on New Year's Eve.

Chen Chen, a Hunan native who has been in Wuhan for three years, joined the volunteer team and was moved by a photo of his best friend. It was New Year's Eve, and a good friend of a nurse who had known Chen for years sent her a photo of herself "fully armed. ". The thick vapor on the protective clothing mask misted my friend's face.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A selfie of a friend of Chen Chen's.

Chat, Chen Chen learned that the friends around the nurses have been infected isolation colleagues, and hospital medical supplies are not enough, "in fact, I am quite afraid of. ". He was so moved by his friend's words that he joined a group of 24 strangers who volunteered to coordinate the transportation of medical supplies in Wuhan.

Chen Chen is one of the investors of an entertainment place in Wuhan. He has a lot of social experience. As messages poured in for Chen, these connections became a powerful resource, connecting with convoys, launching friend circle donations... Chen spent almost 16 hours a day in front of her phone and computer screen, except for sleeping, to handle the allocation of various non-governmental donated materials.

"My typing speed has improved over the past few days. " Chen said he had no time to panic, no time to go out, and no time to talk to those who questioned him.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Some records of working group on Chen Chen Line

Chen Chen is particularly proud of a group of middle school students from Beijing and Shenzhen, chen Chen was handed a large quantity of protective materials, including 2,000 bottles of disinfectant, 500 sets of dupont 1422A / lakelan protective clothing each, 1,000 eye masks, 5,000 surgical masks and 1,000 bottles of disinfectant, he said it gave him a sudden sense of social responsibility.

Chen said the middle school student he contacted was Liu from Beijing, a member of a voluntary organization called Guardian White, which donated the materials. According to a report by Shenzhen television on January 25, the "Guardian White Clothes" voluntary organization has raised more than 190,000 yuan from various fundraising channels. The core 13 members are high school students from Beijing and Shenzhen. They have assembled a temporary "guardian white clothes" group, already contacted many volunteers to carry on the tense material purchase and the distribution work and so on.

Chen Chen wanted to thank them, there are many to thank, but "these days I only have eyes wechat head, no face. ".

A large number of supplies through the temporary team of strange volunteers, relay to the epidemic area of the hospital.

A doctor at the Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University told the reporter that after sending out the message asking for help from the public to accept donations, many donated materials have been received, and the amount of medical materials used is huge. The amount of materials received each day can only guarantee the next 3-4 days or so. But not all the donated goods and materials can be directly used by hospitals. Non-conforming materials will be rejected, or unified custody by the hospital, available materials after inspection was issued to all departments and departments.

Suspected of embezzlement and fraud

The overwhelming amount of information about donations and the material needs of several hospitals are shared online, and a sense of confusion surrounds the volunteers who are involved. In addition to the serious problem of information lag, along with all sorts of doubtful voices the volunteers were stealing.

Chen Zihan, a Hunan native with many years of volunteer experience who now works in the public welfare consulting industry in Shanghai, has a team of more than 30 people working with hundreds of other volunteers.

More than anything else, masks are the most critical and cost effective barrier to respiratory tract infection. Sasa's team volunteered to assist a company in Shenzhen that donated masks to the hospital to conduct fact finding and hospital matching when they learned of the urgent shortage of masks among medical staff in Wuhan.

According to Sasa, the fact finding is that after receiving the applicant's relevant doctor or work certificate, the team will conduct fact checking and allocate resources to the most urgent areas according to the applicant's priorities, based on background data, and volunteers for logistics or shipping. Since January 23 began shipping, Salsa Team within four days to a number of medical structures issued more than 100 million masks.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Chen Zihan surveyed hospital records in Hubei Province on Thursday

For the quality of the company's products, Sasa team will take pictures of the donor product specifications, in advance to the hospital, after the hospital approval, Sasa team contact logistics shipment.

But what makes her "powerless" is that the situation is changing every day. The hospital is still short of masks in the morning and may receive one million masks in the afternoon. The information on the Internet has not been updated, and supplies are still pouring in.

On another occasion, when demand orders for the day were delayed by a day due to logistical constraints and a shortage of staff, Chen Zihan received a phone call calling him a liar.

In recent days, more and more hospitals have been sending out posters accepting donations. Originally, only a number of third-tier hospitals in Wuhan, including the People's Hospital of Wuhan University, issued posters directly through the official wechat and wechat groups, openly soliciting medical supplies such as face masks and protective clothing for the public. Now, hospitals in many counties and cities in Hubei Province, even hospitals in Guangzhou issue posters accepting donations.

"everyone is short of everything, but we just don't know how many hospitals there are, how many are still short? " The Deluge of information made Mei realize that some problems are hard for volunteers to solve and promote, "there needs to be a more efficient mechanism to work with. ".

Programmer volunteers set up docking platform in 4 days

On New Year's Eve, a local group of nearly 500 people in Wuhan did not discuss the Spring Festival gala. Instead, they discussed how to help Wuhan weather the storm.

Bai Yu, a native of Xi'an more than 700 kilometers away, was also invited by his friends to join the "refueling group. " People from all over the country gathered to discuss and make him feel excited.

Bai Yu, an actor who graduated from the Conservatory and is active in the group, got to know several programmers in Wuhan who had the idea to build an information sharing platform for medical supplies.

Soon, on the night of January 25, the first few programmers to build Hubei Medical Supplies Supply and demand information platform prototype and online.

From the first three core programmers, to today's core team of 15 and more than 1,000 volunteers, Bai and his programmer friends and volunteers not only performed three product iterations in four days, information on 308 hospitals in Hubei Province has also been collected and 103 hospitals have been verified so far. The platform volunteer team has a clear division of labor, covering products, front-end, back-end, testing, operating customer service and so on.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The working group of Hubei Medical Material Supply and demand information platform when it was founded

"The construction of the platform is continuous, " Bai said. On the evening of the 26th, after a technical iteration, the 2.0 version of the platform added Logistics Fleet Information, solved problems such as traffic overload, and then went back online. On the 27th, the team continued to pour in fresh power, new programmers and volunteers are well organized.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hubei Medical Material Supply and demand information platform

On the evening of the 28th, Bai posted a platform version 3.0 on his friends'circle. He said the update takes into account the problems of county and city medical supplies being skewed and the national medical supplies shortage, and will add a browsing function so that donors can comprehensively measure the medical supplies distribution, it is also gathering information on health care resource gaps in several provinces except Hubei Province. That's what they built the platform for, and it's being implemented bit by bit.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hubei Medical Material Supply and demand information platform after iteration

Bai and the volunteers'efforts have resulted in a daily iteration of the platform's technology and data, but they still want a stronger, more official organization to run the platform.

Bai and his volunteers are often overwhelmed by the huge collection and verification of hospital information. They are exhausted and even caught a cold from the constant phone calls and wechat messages asking for specifications of medical supplies and information on gaps.

Chen Zihan said the launch of the Hubei Medical Supply and demand information platform was a sign of the Chinese people's strong will, but she also suggested that the government should guide the establishment of a "real-time update platform for matching supply and demand information" to prevent medical supplies from being priced out of the market, directing Society's resources to where they are most needed.

At present, some private donated materials can still be directly docked to the hospital in need. On Hubei Medical Material Requirement information platform, the donor can link up with the hospital according to the verified information.

(Bai Yu and Chen Chen are pseudonyms; Wang Chao and Ding Ning contributed research.)
